Modeling - 2 alphas

Kendra Seaman

3/2/2020

Model Comparison

The majority of participants were best fit by the double-alpha model, but many older adults were not fit well by the model. Many were fit by the baseline (random) model.

Two Alpha Model

Vt+1(x) = Vt(x) +

αgain * max(𝛾 - (rt - Vt(x)), 0) +

αloss * min(𝛾 - (rt - Vt(x)) , 0)

𝛾 = 1 when partner shares, 0 when partner defects

Alphas

No age differences in either alpha, loss: t(71) = 0.71, p = 0.479; loss: t(71) = 0.71, p = 0.479

Betas

No age differences in beta, t(70) = -1.53, p = 0.13

One Alpha Model

Vt+1(x) = Vt(x) + α * (rt - Vt(x))

Alphas

No age differences in alpha, t(69) = -0.31, p = 0.761, or beta, t(70) = 0.38, p = 0.703
